defaultDespite earlier Land Reform legislation and unilateral action by communities like 
defaultEigg
default (of which I was a trustee for eight years), Scotland still has one of the most concentrated patterns of landownership in the developed world. I’m currently researching a
default PhD comparing Norway and Scotland – it would be hard to find a more striking contrast between two neighbouring nations. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOne reason Norway had
default 
defaultone of the widest franchises in Northern Europe was the Constitution
default 
defaultof 1814, which extended the vote to all male
default landowners over the
default 
defaultage of 25 with the result that 45 per cent of men became eligible to vote overnight.
default 
defaultThis compared with 0.173 per cent of Scots enfranchised by the British Reform Bill of 1832. Enfranchising landowners gave the vote to almost half of N
defaultorwegian men but fewer than half
default&#xa0;
defaultof one per cent of Scotsmen in the early 19th century – and the result wouldn’t be very different in either country today.
default 
defaultThe breadth of the Norwegian electorate meant that a cross-section of society had ‘skin in the game’
default and had to be politically accommodated. At first educated
default 
defaultofficials in Oslo looked down on peasants as 
default‘the
default estate of the most foolish’, but soon the liberal intelligentsia joined forces with them to make Government more responsive to Parliament, and forc
defaulte through new, elected, representative municipal councils in 1837 to permanently restrict the local power of central ‘
defaultDanophile
default’ elites and state officials.
default 
defaultThis paved the way for the subsequent development of proportional representation, a political cultu
defaultre of compromise and the embrace of equality as the nation’s guiding social and economic policy objective. In 1814, the average Norwegian man had the vote and owned his farm. The average Scotsman had neither. That continues to have a massive effect on Scot
defaulttish democracy.
